      <abstract displayLabel="Abstract">Accurate and reliable time signals are an essential part of critical
                infrastructure systems in the United States. Because these systems often cannot
                function properly without accurate time signals, timing system failures can have
                serious consequences, with the potential implications including economic loss,
                reduced safety and security, and loss of human life. The primary time
                synchronization sources for these systems are signals broadcast by Global
                Positioning System (GPS) satellites, which has understandably led to concerns about
                our dependency on GPS timing. This report provides an overview of how timing systems
                work and defines some basic terminology and specifications. It then discusses the
                regulatory timing requirements and GPS timing dependencies of United States critical
                infrastructure systems operating in the financial, telecommunications, and electric
                power sectors.</abstract>
